node.text:
“Who rules the wasteland?” asks Lauren and Ben Lindsey, the husband-and-wife duo behind @localhaus and parents of two in this week’s what’s-life-like-for-you-lately profile. “We do! We’re taking it day by day and have instituted end of the world rules.”
?????????
Parenting hack: “When the boys have had enough, they can yell "phone bucket!”, and we have to put them down. We’d almost forgotten what it was like to watch an entire movie without checking in on something really important. You know, like IG. But the twist is that it cuts both ways: when you really need a hug, but your 6 year old happens to be in the zone on Minecraft, you can just yell "phone bucket" and they have to obey the law of the land.” 
?????????
Staycation: “Our fake Universal/Disney vacation where we rode all of the rides via YouTube without the long lines, made Mickey waffles, and refilled our resort mugs with “red juice” a million times for a solid week. And we also got motivated to finally refresh our backyard, allowing us to throw some epic kiddie pool parties.”
?????????
2020 high: “Small road trips to upstate NY to get little doses of fresh air and adventure. Hiking, waterfalls, picnics, playing catch, and just running out all of the energy has become our way to recharge the batteries. Sure we miss early morning movies and breakfast at Alamo Drafthouse, but it turns out the great outdoors still has some magic left. Huzzah!”
?????????
Fall plans: “We are heading into the Fall with caution. We’ll be remote learning, masking up, and looking to get free in the streets safely as often as we can while counting down the days until 2021. End of the world rules still apply.”
?????????
Pay it forward: favorite IG accounts? “@thelocalproject because pretty homes make us happy; @condenasttraveller because we can at least dream; @slow_roads because it gives us feels; @celestbarber because of course!”

Plantation Industries and Commodities Minister Datuk Dr Mohd Khairuddin Aman Razali has apologised for violating the 14-day #quarantine rule and will be returning his salary as a minister from May to August to show his remorse.⁣
⁣
Khairuddin - who recently came under fire for skipping quarantine after returning from Turkey in July - said on Saturday (Aug 22) that the forfeited salary will be given to the national #Covid19 fund under the Health Ministry.⁣
⁣
“Referring to the Health Ministry’s press statement on the issue of the recovery #MCO #SOPs today, I apologise to all Malaysians for the mistake that has occurred," he said.⁣
⁣
Full story in our Instastory⁣.

node.text:
Are you struggling with lockdown easing?⁠
⁠
Don't worry you aren't alone! My anxiety has been through the roof, as the UK slowly eases restrictions. As someone who has been in quarantine since February, it's difficult to feel safe in the outside world. I'm also worried about people forgetting just how difficult it is for those of us with Chronic Illnesses who often spend much of our time housebound.⁠
⁠
Just remember that your feelings are valid, and it will be okay ?⁠
⁠
Link to the blog post is in the bio! ?⁠
.⁠
.⁠

node.text:
Reposted from @sokarlnerry It was a magical morning at the Falls. When we arrived the night before, though it was beautiful it was also crowded. After only four hours of sleep, we woke up at 5am! We were fatigued from the road, and not really looking forward to the drive back home, but we promised to at least give the Falls one last look. So we checked out of our hotel room, and made our way back to the edge. There, we were greeted with a beautiful sunrise and a rainbow. No one else in sight, just us two. The rainbow as our emblem made so much sense that morning. This enchanting thing right before our eyes which we couldn’t describe or explain, and only feel. It stood out from anything else the eye could see, so boldly and colorfully. It owned its presence and demanded to be acknowledged. Its colors showing spectrum, individuality, and inclusivity. Nothing mystical about it as it is undoubtedly and undeniably real. So yes, the rainbow is the perfect symbol for WHO WE ARE. And that morning at the Falls, God or the universe or who/whatever reminded us to be PROUD of that. ????
.
.
.

We must eliminate stereotypes that men are better in the workplace and a womens role is to be home raising children/cooking/cleaning. Men and women BOTH have potential to be parental figures AND succeeding in their careers. Each household has the decision of whether the man or woman fulfils different parental roles (cooking, cleaning, disciplining, working and/or paying bills) depending on their personal skills! Gender stereotypes and societal judgement creates limitations for men to be loving, sympathetic, multitaskers, and women to be business savvy, strong and determined…so we must eliminate this judgement so we can all be free to express our skills and what we are destined to achieve in life.
